'''Lakha''' ({{bo|t=ལ་ཁ་|w=la kha}} "language of the mountain pass", also called "Tshangkha") is a [[Tibetic languages#Classification|Southern Tibetic language]] spoken by about 8,000 people in [[Wangdue Phodrang District|Wangdue Phodrang]] and [[Trongsa District]]s in central [[Bhutan]].<ref name=vanDriem93>{{cite web|url=http://repository.forcedmigration.org/pdf/?pid=fmo:3003 |format=PDF |last=van Driem |first=George L. |authorlink=George van Driem |title=Language Policy in Bhutan |publisher=[[School of Oriental and African Studies|SOAS]] |location=[[London]] |year=1993 |accessdate=2011-01-18}}</ref><ref name=e18>{{e18|lkh}}</ref> Lakha is spoken by descendants of pastoral [[yak]]herd communities.<ref name=vanDriem93/>
